Text Analytics Final Project¶

HOYA 8: Taylor Whitelow¶

08 October 2023¶

You are leading a new branded hotel and you need to know what customers who give poor reviews of hotels tend to bring up. To minimize poor service, your analytics team will examine hotel reviews using topic modeling to identify what reviewers who give poor reviews actually write about in their experience to ensure your hotel focuses special attention and ensures high-quality services in those domains.¶

You will use the Yelp hotel reviews data to build a presentation to present to technical and non-technical co-workers and managers. The presentation should be professional and succinct (about 12 minutes) and focus on the problem at hand including:¶

  • #### What topics do reviewers tend to bring up in general?
  • #### How do happy customers differ from unhappy customers in the topics they bring up in their review?
  • #### Are there other characteristics about customers that would be useful to know about?
  • #### Based on the results and what should your new hotel focus on?
  • #### What are the main takeaways and recommendations?

You will deliver the results as a professional, team-based presentation. You should discuss the background of the problem, any important processing and modeling steps you made to arrive at your results, the key results and insights, and a set of recommendations moving forward. Your presentation should be 10 minutes and recorded. You will submit two files: (1) the recorded presentation; and (2) the code you used for your analysis.¶

In [3]:
#Function to remove punctuation and convert to lower case
def clean_text(t):
    import re
    
    t = t.lower()
    t = re.sub("[()!?]", "", t)        #remove punctuation
    t = re.sub("\[.*?\]", "", t)       #remove puncutation
    t = re.sub("[^a-z]", " ", t)       #remove anything that is not a letter
    return t

In [6]:
#Remove stopwords

#Import and read in stopwords
sw = stopwords.words("english")

#Add additional stopwords to stopword list
sw.extend(["hotel", "stay", "stayed", "room"])

#Filter out stopwords and save result in text_clean
df['text_clean'] = df['text_clean'].apply(lambda each: ' '.join([each for each in each.split() if each not in (sw)]))
df_pos['text_clean'] = df_pos['text_clean'].apply(lambda each: ' '.join([each for each in each.split() if each not in (sw)]))
df_neg['text_clean'] = df_neg['text_clean'].apply(lambda each: ' '.join([each for each in each.split() if each not in (sw)]))

Step 3 - Vectorize Text/Create gensim Dictionary¶

In [20]:
#Create gensim dictionary with tokens and ids (map frequency of unique words to ids)
dictionary = Dictionary(df["text_tokenized"])
dictionary_pos = Dictionary(df_pos["text_tokenized"])
dictionary_neg = Dictionary(df_neg["text_tokenized"])
In [21]:
#Filter dictionary to keep only terms found in at least 20% and no more than 80% of documents
dictionary.filter_extremes(no_below=0.2, no_above=0.8)
dictionary_pos.filter_extremes(no_below=0.2, no_above=0.8)
dictionary_neg.filter_extremes(no_below=0.2, no_above=0.8)

#Create gensim corpus (i.e. a doc-term matrix), uses bag of words with token ids and tf
gensim_corpus = [dictionary.doc2bow(doc) for doc in df["text_tokenized"]]
gensim_corpus_pos = [dictionary_pos.doc2bow(doc) for doc in df_pos["text_tokenized"]]
gensim_corpus_neg = [dictionary_neg.doc2bow(doc) for doc in df_neg["text_tokenized"]]

Step 4 - Instantiate LDA with Parameters and Fit Model¶

In [22]:
#Hyperparameter Tuning
for each in range(2, 11):
    ldamodel = LdaModel(corpus = gensim_corpus,
                   num_topics = each,
                   id2word = dictionary,
                   random_state = 757)
    coh = CoherenceModel(model = ldamodel,
                    texts = df["text_tokenized"],
                    dictionary = dictionary,
                    coherence = 'c_v')
    print(f"With {each} topics, Coherence: {coh.get_coherence()}")

#Fit model

                   num_topics = 3,
                   id2word = dictionary,
                   random_state = 757)

                   num_topics = 2,
                   id2word = dictionary_pos,
                   random_state = 757)

ldamodel_neg = LdaModel(corpus = gensim_corpus_neg,
                   num_topics = 8,
                   id2word = dictionary_neg,
                   random_state = 757)

# pyLDAvis
  # Relevance: relevance is a weighted average of the 
#        logarithms of a term's probability 
#       and the ratio of a term's probability within a topic 
#      to its marginal probability across the corpus
#      (i.e. how relevant is that word to that particular topic)
# Left panel: 
    # global view of topic model
    # centers of circle are distance between topics then projected onto two PCA dimensions
    # area of circles is the overall prevalence of the topic in the whole topic model
    # examine how prevalent each topic is (size of bubble)
    # examine how topics relate to each other (overlap or distance)
# Right panel:
    # Bars represent individual terms that are most useful for interpreting selected topic on left
    # Blue bar represents corpus wide frequencies
    # Red bar represents topic-specific frequencies
    # examine the meaning of each topic

# Classify each document by its "top" topic and create new column with topic classification
df["topic"] = [sorted(ldamodel[gensim_corpus][each])[0][0] for each in range(len(df["text_tokenized"]))]
df_pos["topic"] = [sorted(ldamodel_pos[gensim_corpus_pos][each])[0][0] for each in range(len(df_pos["text_tokenized"]))]
df_neg["topic"] = [sorted(ldamodel_neg[gensim_corpus_neg][each])[0][0] for each in range(len(df_neg["text_tokenized"]))]

                                   "Topic 3"))
